A Global Study of COVID-19 Effects vs Dietary Composition (CMSC320 Final Tutorial)¶

By: Danesh Sivakumar

“Health requires healthy food."

- Roger Williams (1603 – 1683) [he lived a pretty long time!]

Introduction¶

The COVID-19 pandemic has brought about unprecedented times; the extremely rapid spread of the disease during 2019-2020 was devastating worldwide. Particularly affected were countries with low socioeconomic standing; due to mass panic and a lack of reliable information, many individuals in these countries were unable to take proper precautions and thus unfortunately suffered adverse consequences. It is no coincidence that many of these countries that were affected are also burdened by another pandemic: food insecurity.

Having been raised in a rural village in India, my father was no stranger to nights without dinner. Droughts and a lack of access to clean drinking water certainly didn't contribute positively to his family's hunger. In spite of the fact that it has been over forty years since those times, not much has improved. Many people in developing countries are in food deserts, and do not have access to reliable healthy sources of food; as such, they are forced to either starve or make do with unhealthy sustenance. World hunger has been a problem for decades now, but it is an especially pressing matter at this time and day.

In this project, I aim to investigate deeper this trend between food habits and different COVID-19 statistics, conditined on country. In particular, I want to look for trends in the data and establish statistically significant results that demonstrate relationships between the aforementioned parameters.

1: Data Collection/Curation¶

1.A: Libraries¶

First, we need to import the necessary libraries:

  • pandas: lets us use dataframes to manipulate and display the data
  • numpy: helps us perform computationally efficient array operations
  • matplotlib: allows for effective data visualization
  • statsmodels: lets us perform statistical tests and measure the significance of our results

In [38]:
fat_supply_names = duplicate_names.copy()
food_supply_names = duplicate_names.copy()
protein_supply_names = duplicate_names.copy()

for i in range(1, len(duplicate_names)):
    fat_supply_names[i] = duplicate_names[i] + " (FAT)"
    food_supply_names[i] = duplicate_names[i] + " (FOOD)"
    protein_supply_names[i] = duplicate_names[i] + " (PROTEIN)"

column_dict_fat = dict(zip(duplicate_names, fat_supply_names))
column_dict_food = dict(zip(duplicate_names, food_supply_names))
column_dict_protein = dict(zip(duplicate_names, protein_supply_names))

df_fat_supply.rename(columns=column_dict_fat, inplace=True)
df_food_supply.rename(columns=column_dict_food, inplace=True)
df_protein_supply.rename(columns=column_dict_protein, inplace=True)

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

With so much data at our disposal, a fair question to ask is "what do we do with all of this information?" A natural start is to figure out how much fat and protein each country consumes. How can we do that?

It's time to do some math! Let $\textbf{c} := (c_1,\cdots,c_n)$ be the $n$ foods categories in the dataset, and let $\textbf{a} := (a_1, \cdots, a_n)$ be a vector of the percentage consumption of food, where entry $a_i$ corresponds to the percentage of food category $c_i$ that is consumed. If $\textbf{f} := (f_1, \cdots, f_n)$ is a vector of the percentage fat contributed to the diet, where entry $f_i$ corresponds to the percentage of fat contributed by food $c_i$ in a country's average diet, it follows that the average percentage of fat in the country's diet, taken over all foods in the dataset is the dot product of the two vectors, namely $$\langle a, f\rangle = \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i \cdot f_i$$ We can play a similar game for a vector of protein percentage contributions, by letting $\textbf{p} := (p_1, \cdots, p_n)$ be a vector of the percentage protein contributed to the diet and computing another dot product.

We will now implement this in Python using the helpful zip function to join the lists element-by-element.

In [41]:
country_protein_percent = {}

for idx, row in df.iterrows():
    total = 0
    for pair in zip(food_supply_names[1:], protein_supply_names[1:]):
        total += row[pair[0]]/100 * row[pair[1]]/100 
    country_protein_percent[row['Country']] = total*100

country_protein_percent

These numbers do intuitively check out; they are real numbers between 0 and 1, so it makes sense that they represent percentage consumption of certain food groups. Furthermore, the calculations are mathematically sound; the inner product notation is just another way of representing a weighted average of percentages, which is what we desired. Of course, this is based on the assumption that the food categories in the dataset are exhaustive—I think this is a reasonable assumption to make, given the fact that the percentages of food categories roughly add up to 100%.

Now, we can start to visualize this data. There's a lot to choose from here!

In [44]:

It appears that directly plotting confirmed COVID cases against fat percentage in diet doesn't yield much interesting data. Why could this be the case? It seems that the trend is almost flat; at a first glance, this implies that the percentage of fat doesn't affect the number of COVID cases. However, upon a closer look, we can see that this data is missing a crucial piece of information: the country population! This would explain why there isn't much change in the vertical axis; it's because different countries have vastly different populations, and the scale is much larger! Let's try calculating the COVID infection rate by dividing the raw number of cases by the population of the country, and then plotting this data.

In order to do this, we will use the pypopulation library to grab population data. Note that we could also do this by scraping data from the web, but this is an easier alternative, as there is no need to clean up the data. Furthermore, we will also scrape the country codes from Wikipedia for our reference.

In [45]:
import pypopulation

codes = pd.read_csv('http://geohack.net/gis/wikipedia-iso-country-codes.csv')
codes.rename(columns={'English short name lower case': "Country"}, inplace=True)
codes.drop(columns=['ISO 3166-2', 'Alpha-3 code', 'Numeric code'], inplace=True)

df = pd.merge(df, codes, on='Country', how='inner')
In [46]:
df['Population'] = df.apply(lambda row: pypopulation.get_population(str(row['Alpha-2 code'])), axis=1)

Awesome! Now that we have this information, we can normalize the COVID data by dividing by population, and multiplying by a constant factor (say, 100,000). While we're at it, we'll also create a new dataframe and drop the columns that are no longer of interest to tidy things up.

In [47]:
columns_to_get_rid_of = fat_supply_names + protein_supply_names + food_supply_names
for i in range(3):
    columns_to_get_rid_of.remove('Country')
df_useful = df.drop(columns=columns_to_get_rid_of)
df_useful['Confirmed Rate'] = df_useful.apply(lambda row: (row['Confirmed']/row['Population']) * 100000, axis=1)
df_useful['Death Rate'] = df_useful.apply(lambda row: (row['Deaths']/row['Population']) * 100000, axis=1)
df_useful['Recovery Rate'] = df_useful.apply(lambda row: (row['Recovered']/row['Population']) * 100000, axis=1)
df_useful.drop(columns=['Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Recovered', 'Active'], inplace=True)
df_useful.rename(columns={'Alpha-2 code': 'Code'}, inplace=True)
df_useful

It seems like the shape of our data is roughly the same in all of these plots; this seems to indicate that there is indeed a trend between COVID data and dietary composition. In particular, it seems that there is a negative linear relationship between percentage of fat/protein diet and the COVID-metrics; in other words, more protein/fat leads to fewer COVID cases and deaths. Let's investigate this a bit deeper in more detail.

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

In this scenario, the null hypothesis is that there is no statistically significant relationship between fat/protein consumption and COVID numbers. In other words, the null hypothesis asserts that any correlation is due to chance.

In order to analyze the effectiveness of our data, let's perform a linear regression for each of the six combinations of data that we considered. We can perform this using statsmodels, and extract the relevant information when needed.

In [54]:
y_death = np.nan_to_num(np.array(deaths))
x_protein = np.nan_to_num(np.array(protein))
x_protein = sm.add_constant(x_protein)

protein_death = sm.OLS(y_death, x_protein).fit()
intercept_p_value = protein_death.pvalues[0]
death_p_value = protein_death.pvalues[1]
print(protein_death.summary()) 
# Look at the 'coef' column for the line-of-best-fit; the model tells us the equation!
print()
b, m = protein_death.params
print("y = " + str(m) + "*x + " + str(b))
print("p-value is " + str(death_p_value))

As an example, we print the summary of the regression results above. In the example, the explanatory variable is percentage of protein consumption in diet, and the response variable is the number of COVID deaths per hundred thousand. We can see that the slope term is negative, supporting the conjecture that an increase of protein percentage in diet contributes to a decrease in COVID deaths.

Furthermore, the p-value is less than 0.05, indicating that the results are statistically significant for this combination with an alpha value of 0.05.

Because we don't need to print out the summary statistics each time, let's write a method to perform the linear regression and store the results in a dataframe:

In [55]:
def linear_regression (x, y, explanatory, response):
    y = np.nan_to_num(np.array(y))
    x = np.nan_to_num(np.array(x))
    x = sm.add_constant(x)
    model = sm.OLS(y, x).fit()
    intercept_p_value = model.pvalues[0] # we dont need this
    p_value = model.pvalues[1]
    b, m = model.params
    equation = "y = " + str(m) + "*x + " + str(b)
    return np.array([explanatory, response, equation, p_value])

combinations = [[protein, deaths, 'Protein', 'COVID Deaths'], [protein, confirmed, 'Protein', 'COVID Cases'], [protein, recovered, 'Protein', 'COVID Recoveries'], [fat, deaths, 'Fat', 'COVID Deaths'], [fat, confirmed, 'Fat', 'COVID Cases'], [fat, recovered, 'Fat', 'COVID Recoveries']]
results = np.array([[0, 0, 0, 0]])
for combination in combinations:
    y = combination[1]
    x = combination[0]
    explanatory = combination[2]
    response = combination[3]
    res = linear_regression(x, y, explanatory, response)
    results = np.append(results, [res], axis=0)
results = results[1:]

As we can see in the dataframe above, the results are similar for every combination of explanatory and response variable. We see that in all cases, the slope of the least squares regression line is negative, and the P-value is ≤ 0.05, so that the models have statistical significance with an alpha threshhold of 0.05. In other words, we can reject the null hypothesis, and conclude that there is a statistically significant relationship between each explanatory and response variable considered.

5. Communication of insights attained¶

Initially, I had anticipated that more fat would contribute to worse COVID case/death rates and more protein would contribute to better COVID case/death rates; this is because, classically fat is associated with negative effects and protein is associated with strength, so I thought the former would exacerbate COVID symptoms while the latter would improve them. However, it appears as though this one-dimensional approach does not hold true; rather, a higher dietary percentage of both protein and fat is correlated with a decreased in COVID infection and death rate with high statistical significance.

I had also originally thought that healthier food choices would contribute to a greater rate of COVID recovery. This did not turn out to be the case; the trend for COVID recovery was similar to the other response variables. This is probably due to the fact that COVID recovery is also conditional on COVID infection; the former cannot happen without the latter occuring. An interesting extension would be to consider a multi-linear model, and perhaps calculate additional metrics of measuring response variables–for example, dividing the recovery rate by the infection rate.

In spite of the contrast of the data results to my original hypothesis, I do believe it is overall consistent and makes sense; this is because fat is not necessarily always a bad thing! More fat and protein consumption could actually be an indicator of a country's socioeconomic status; more well-off countries would have access to better (and more) food supplies; thus having more access to these food sources would increase the relative percentage composition in diet, and also improve COVID infection/death rates.

All in all, the data do reveal an important point I mentioned earlier: the importance of health amid the COVID-19 pandemic cannot be understated. More so now than ever, having access to healthy food is critical; nourishment is essential to living a healthy life, and as we can see from the data, a lack of presence of important food groups in one's diet can exacerbate the impacts of COVID. Certainly these results can be applied outside of the scope of the COVID pandemic, but it is especially important now to fight hard in the global war against world hunger. After all, health requires healthy food.
